metadata.name: Spira #201
metadata.description:
Spira is a series of static pieces where lines are drawn symmetrically around a central pivot. Additionally it is possible for the piece to be "broken" in which case some of the symmetry is lost and instead a more complex asymmetrical piece is produced.

Features:
> Brokenness (A percentage to indicate how "broken" the piece is.)
> Rotation (Rotation of each iteration.)
> Palette (Colour palette.)
> Sectors (Number of sectors which form the rotational symmetry.)
> Iterations (Number of iterations - higher means more lines in each sector.)
> Spacing (The spacing between each iteration.)

Created by Lucas RiedlShah (@lucas_riedlshah)

metadata.name: Currency 1.0 #78
metadata.description:
Currency 1.0

This is one of a series of conceptual artworks about art and valuation. Each artwork is an exact replica of itself, so all the generative pieces look and feel the same. This work references Fxhash & Tezos eco-system and thus each token is fictionally named as FXT, but it has no relation to the official platforms. 

This artwork attempts to questions the basic premise of art valuation - does art have any value if the art itself costs nothing? Is the value of art what the anyone wants to pay for the work? Is art itself the currency, or is currency the art?

There are 2500 editions in Currency 1.0, with each edition costing 0 XTZ. 
Royalty is 10%, the minimum permitted.

Currency 1.0 @beardcoded

metadata.name: Postcards from Gaza #15
metadata.description:
A generative artwork that evokes devastation and suffering. The composition, created in 3D using a combinatory generation technique, depicts a pseudo-architectural structure â€” or what remains of it â€” emerging from a blood-red fog.
The piece is directly inspired by the ongoing tragedy in the Gaza Strip, reflecting on the devastating impact of armed conflicts on urban life, people, and the very essence of dwelling. "Postcards from Gaza" is not just an abstract artwork: it is a statement, a form of memory, and an act of protest, written in the language of generative art.

metadata.name: Mandala "Celestial Harmony" #10
metadata.description:
Discover the mesmerizing world of "Celestial Harmony," a generative art collection where ancient symbolism meets modern digital creativity. This series, crafted for fxhash, invites art collectors to explore the profound beauty of mandalas through intricate, algorithmically generated designs that evoke balance, unity, and spiritual depth.

What is a Mandala?
The mandala, derived from the ancient Sanskrit word for "circle," is a sacred symbol found across cultures, from Tibetan Buddhism to Native American traditions. It represents the universe, wholeness, and the journey toward inner harmony. Traditionally, mandalas are symmetrical, geometric patterns that radiate from a central point, often used in meditation to focus the mind and connect with the divine. Their hypnotic designs draw the viewer inward, offering a sense of peace and contemplation.

In this collection, each mandala is a unique, algorithmically generated masterpiece, blending traditional symmetry with contemporary aesthetics. The artworks feature:
â€¢	Dynamic Layers and Patterns: Multiple layers of petals, waves, spirals, and radial forms create a sense of depth and motion, drawing the eye toward the center.
â€¢	Harmonious Color Palettes: Choose from six distinct styles, ranging from soft pastels (blues, pinks, mint greens) to vibrant triadic hues (red, green, blue) and bold complementary tones (purple and yellow). Each palette is carefully curated to evoke emotional resonanceâ€”whether calming, energizing, or grounding.
â€¢	Central Flower Motif: At the heart of each mandala blooms a delicate flower, symbolizing growth and renewal, surrounded by intricate, symmetrical patterns that radiate outward like cosmic energy.
â€¢	Subtle Variations: Small, intentional imperfections in symmetry and curvature add an organic, handcrafted feel, making each piece feel alive and unique.

metadata.name: Reading a book #157
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.
